                <h2>Answer These 3 Questions Before Allocating Budget</h2>
<p>Before spending money, spend 10 minutes answering these questions to make your budget allocation more rational:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Are you in testing or growth phase?</strong> The first 8 weeks of a new product launch is the testing phase, where budgets should focus on creative testing. After stabilization, enter the growth phase and increase scale spending.</li>
<li><strong>What is your average order value?</strong> Products with AOV below $50 don't need heavy retargeting budgets. Products with AOV above $150 typically see better retargeting ROI.</li>
<li><strong>What percentage of your traffic is organic?</strong> If organic traffic exceeds 30%, you can reduce pressure on paid acquisition budgets.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Before allocating budget, ensure you have at least 4 weeks of advertising data or clear category benchmarks. Budget allocation without data is gambling.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Step 1: Set Budget Percentages by Channel</h2>
<p>E-commerce websites typically advertise across 3-4 channels. Budget percentages depend on your product type and customer profile:</p>
<h3>Budget Reference by Channel</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Channel</th>
<th>Testing Phase</th>
<th>Growth Phase</th>
<th>Best For</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Meta (Facebook/Instagram)</td>
<td>40-50%</td>
<td>35-45%</td>
<td>Fast-moving goods, fashion, home, tools</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Google Ads (Search + Shopping)</td>
<td>20-30%</td>
<td>30-40%</td>
<td>Products with clear search intent</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>TikTok</td>
<td>10-20%</td>
<td>15-25%</td>
<td>Young audience, novel products</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Retargeting (Cross-channel)</td>
<td>10-15%</td>
<td>15-20%</td>
<td>High AOV, longer decision cycles</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Practical Allocation Example</h3>
<p>A utility app e-commerce site with $10,000 monthly budget, AOV around $80:</p>
<ul>
<li>Meta Ads: $4,500 (new creative testing + scaling winners)</li>
<li>Google Search: $2,500 (brand keywords + competitor terms)</li>
<li>TikTok: $1,500 (short video creative testing)</li>
<li>Retargeting Pool: $1,500 (visitor recapture + cart abandonment)</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> After allocation, verify each channel can cover the minimum testing unit. Meta ad set daily budget should be at least $20, Google Search at least $15, otherwise the algorithm cannot learn effectively.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Step 2: Split Testing vs. Scaling Budgets</h2>
<p>Within each channel, divide the budget into two parts:</p>
<h3>Budget Split Formula</h3>
<p><strong>Testing Budget (20-30%):</strong> For testing new creatives, new audience packages, new targeting countries</p>
<ul>
<li>Maximum per test project = Monthly budget × 5%</li>
<li>Testing period: 2-3 weeks, no additions or early termination</li>
<li>Success criteria: CTR &gt; 1.5%, CPM &lt; $15</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Scaling Budget (70-80%):</strong> For expanding proven winning combinations</p>
<ul>
<li>Only increase budget for ad sets with positive ROI</li>
<li>Single increment should not exceed 30% of original budget</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Every Monday, check testing budget consumption. If testing budget isn't spent within 2 weeks, creative quality is likely poor and needs replacement.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Step 3: Establish Budget Timing Rhythm</h2>
<h3>Monthly Budget Cycle</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Timing</th>
<th>Key Action</th>
<th>Purpose</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>1st of month</td>
<td>Last month's data review, set this month's allocation</td>
<td>Avoid惯性投放</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>7th of month</td>
<td>First round budget adjustment (+/- 20%)</td>
<td>Eliminate underperformers</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>15th of month</td>
<td>Mid-term review, check channel ROI trends</td>
<td>Prevent budget waste</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Last week</td>
<td>Reserve 10% for Black Friday-style promotions</td>
<td>Capture seasonal traffic</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Emergency Adjustment Triggers</h3>
<p>Reassess budget allocation immediately when:</p>
<ul>
<li>A channel's CPA rises more than 20% for 3 consecutive days</li>
<li>An ad set's ROAS stays below breakeven for 2+ weeks</li>
<li>Competitors increase spending in key markets</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Checkpoint:</strong> Record the reason and results of each budget adjustment. After 3 months, you'll have your own budget adjustment SOP.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>This Week's Action Checklist</h2>
<p>After reading this article, execute these steps immediately:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Export last 30 days of ad data, calculate CPA and ROAS by channel</li>
<li>[ ] Compare current allocation against the reference percentages</li>
<li>[ ] Split testing budget from scaling budget</li>
<li>[ ] Set a Monday 9 AM calendar reminder for budget check</li>
<li>[ ] Record the decision basis for this budget adjustment</li>
</ul>
<p>Budget allocation is not a one-time decision—it's a weekly iteration process. Use this checklist to clarify your thinking first, then gradually build your own advertising rhythm.</p>
